				ARMY TRAINING
			<div></center>


		<div id="first">
			<div id="photo_one">
				<div id="info_one">
			</div>
				
					<div id="hover_one"> <p>Basic Training was a real disapointment. I thought it was more akin to summer camp than it was combat training. It was mostly just overworked Drill Sergeants telling you about how cool they are while subsequently teaching you nothing of real practical value. Back in High School I went through an 11-day search and rescue boot camp with my local Sherrif department, that experience was far more difficult and rewarding than the 9 weeks of Army Basic.</p> </div>
				
				<center>

					<img id="fire_one" src="scanned_docs/training/bct.png">
				</center>
			</div>
		</div>
			
		<div id="second">
			<div id="photo_two">
				<div id="info_two">
			</div>
				
					<div id="hover_two"> <p>This certificate mostly reminds me of the people who did not acheive the standards expected of them and were still allowed to graduate. Example: there was a Soldier in my graduating class who lacked the strength necessary to pull back the charging handle on their rifle. Capably operating a rifle is a minumum essential task for a Soldier, failure to do so is completely unacceptabl. </p> </div>
				
				<center>

					<img id="fire_two" src="scanned_docs/training/sotc.png">
				</center>
			</div>
		</div>

		<div id="third">
			<div id="photo_three">
				<div id="info_three">
			</div>
				
					<div id="hover_three"> <p>Some people might be suprised to see this, but yes, the Department of Defense has a school (The Defense Information School) dedicated to the communication arts. Covering topics such as: Photography, Video Production, Broadcasting, Journalism, and Graphic Design. Although this school tends to deemphasize the more creative aspects of this line of work, I actually commend this school's ability to establish a solid and disciplined technical foundtaion in its Students.</p> </div>
				
				<center>

					<img id="fire_three" src="scanned_docs/training/bsp.png">
				</center>
			</div>
		</div>

		<div id="fourth">
			<div id="photo_four">
				<div id="info_four">
			</div>
				
					<div id="hover_four"> <p> My grades in this course don't show it, but I almost failed. If you fail any test twice you fail the course and are recycled to the class behind you. I was not a very strong photographer early on, and I still today I have a long way to go in my development. I failed my first attempt at our final exam due to two minor mistakes in my caption writing that compounded over 10 different photos. That goes back to what I said above about the technical discipline the school sought to instill in its students.</p> </div>
				
				<center>

					<img id="fire_four" src="scanned_docs/training/bsp_grades.png">
				</center>
			</div>
		</div>

