		<div id="sixth">
			<div id="photo_six">
				<div id="info_six">
				</div>
				
					<div id="hover_six"> <p> There was once upon a time that being airborne meant you were an elite troop; World War 2, and that is basically it. Static line parachuting is such an easy skill to learn there is no reason why it is not a requirement for every single Soldier. In addition, airborne operations should be limited to only what is necessary to maintain the proficiency of jumpers, jump masters, parachute riggers, and pilots. Some airborne units and individuals focus to heavily on conducting airborne operations and jump an excessive amount. The long term health risks associated with the ground impact following a static line jump need to be considered. </p> </div>
				
				<center>

					<img id="fire_six" src="scanned_docs/training/jump_cert.png">
				</center>
			</div>
		</div>

		<div id="seventh">
			<div id="photo_seven">
				<div id="info_seven">
				</div>
				
					<div id="hover_seven"> <p> This course was crucial in developing my capabilities and confidence in handling my weapon. It was one week of nothing but putting rounds down range in a variety of scenarios; from basic marksmanship to complex shoot move and communicate scenarios emphasizing efficent magazine changes, effective use of cover, ambidextrous shooting, and immediate action in the event of a weapon malfunction. This course took everything I learned in basic training about marksmanship and reformated it in a way that actually made sense. </p> </div>
				
				<center>

					<img id="fire_seven" src="scanned_docs/training/cstc.png">
				</center>
			</div>
		</div>

		<div id="eigth">
			<div id="photo_eight">
				<div id="info_eight">
				</div>
				
					<div id="hover_eight"> <p> I did not actually attend this course. I was seperately given a brief crash course on the fighting techniques taught during the training. I showed up on the final day and somewhat convincingly stumbled my way through the evaluation. I could tell the instructor was reluctant to sign off on me, but he ultimately did. </p> </div>
				
				<center>

					<img id="fire_eight" src="scanned_docs/training/ctc.png">
				</center>
			</div>
		</div>

		<div id="ninth">
			<div id="photo_nine">
				<div id="info_nine">
				</div>
				
					<div id="hover_nine"> <p> The one time I drove a bus, after being certified, I hit a pole and another bus while trying to back up. Luckily, I was just returning the bus to the bus yard and no one was on board. The damage wasn't even noticeable.</p> </div>
				
				<center>

					<img id="fire_nine" src="scanned_docs/training/bus.png">
				</center>
			</div>
		</div>

		<div id="tenth">
			<div id="photo_ten">
				<div id="info_ten">
				</div>
				
					<div id="hover_ten"> <p> This wasn't a military course, but my unit paid for me and a fellow Soldier to attend this weeklong workshop at Maine Media College located in Rockport, Maine. It was a fun experience getting far outside of the military sphere of influence to work with a diverse blend of civillian artists from all over the country. The experience was definitely a turning point in my overall career in visual communications. I'm grateful to the individuals in my unit who helped in getting the workshop approved and funded.</p> </div>
				
				<center>

					<img id="fire_ten" src="scanned_docs/training/maine_media.png">
